{
  "answer": "Surah Al-Qamar repeatedly establishes that God designed the text for memorization, stating, \"And We have certainly made the Qur\u2019\u0101n easy for remembrance, so is there any who will remember?\" [1-3]. God also assumed direct responsibility for the Prophet's ability to memorize the revelation, instructing him not to move his tongue hastily and promising, \"Indeed, upon Us is its collection [in your heart] and [to make possible] its recitation\" [4, 5]. \n\nThe absolute protection of the text is guaranteed by the divine decree: \"Indeed, it is We who sent down the Qur\u2019\u0101n and indeed, We will be its guardian\" [6]. Furthermore, the scriptures anchor the necessity of its specific linguistic preservation, explaining that it was revealed in a \"clear Arabic language\" so that the people could comprehend its message [7, 8]. Surah Yusuf explicitly states, \"Indeed, We have sent it down as an Arabic Qur\u2019\u0101n that you might understand\" [9]. Guided by these foundational verses, the Prophet Muhammad and thousands of his companions memorized the text entirely, ensuring an unbroken oral and written preservation of the exact Arabic revelation [6, 10].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
  "turn_number": 1,
  "is_follow_up": true,
